description:
Customer report: [https://jira.mongodb.org/browse/HELP-89527]

Environment: AWS Lambda (Node 20.x, 15-minute timeout), MongoDB Data Federation (Atlas) via AWS PrivateLink. Long-running `$out` aggregation into S3.

 

Timelines

6.15 (6.16 would work the same):
 * CommandStarted, aggregation
 * Data Federation completes in ~6 min
 * CommandSucceeded, aggregation

6.17:
 * CommandStarted, aggregation
 * Data Federation completes in ~6 min
 * ...
 * Lambda timeout (15 min)

 

What have changed ([https://github.com/mongodb/node-mongodb-native/pull/4510/changes#diff-7cc25e5d3247913cdf1fe1e7788e951e4435bb1091d6b8aef135c4b171c7c997):]

makeSocket() explicitly called setKeepAlive and setNoDelay on all sockets after creation:
{code:javascript}
socket.setKeepAlive(true, 300000);
socket.setTimeout(connectTimeoutMS);
socket.setNoDelay(noDelay);
{code}
After the change (6.17 and onwards):
{code:javascript}
result.keepAliveInitialDelay ??= 120000;
result.keepAlive = true;
result.noDelay = options.noDelay ?? true;

socket.setTimeout(connectTimeoutMS);

// both calls have been removed
// socket.setKeepAlive(true, 300000);
// socket.setNoDelay(noDelay);
{code}
 

tls.connect() does not applies keepAlive and keepAliveInitialDelay from constructor options - these options are silently ignored ([https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/62003).]

 

It happened with AWS PrivateLink because it has a 350-second idle connection timeout ([https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/networking-and-content-delivery/implementing-long-running-tcp-connections-within-vpc-networking/).] Without keepAlive during the long-running server-side operation (6 minutes aggregation) there is no data flowing, so the NLB drops the TCP connection. The server sends data into dead connection, and the client socket has no way to know that connection is gone.

 

Fix: we should restore explicit setKeepAlive and setNoDelay calls in makeSocket() after socket creation.
{code:javascript}
socket.setKeepAlive(true, options.keepAliveInitialDelay ?? 120_000);
socket.setTimeout(connectTimeoutMS);
socket.setNoDelay(options.noDelay ?? true);
{code}
There is no easy way to create integration test for this (as NLB drops TCP connection), new unit test should verify that setKeepAlive and setNoDelay are called on sockets produced by makeSocket for both: TLS and non-TLS connections.

See ENGSEC-670. To be addressed by March 22.
h2. Summary

The MongoDB Node.js driver's OIDC authentication includes a host allowlist mechanism to ensure tokens are only sent to trusted servers. The hostMatchesWildcards() function validates hostnames against wildcard patterns (e.g., *.mongodb.net). However, the implementation uses a permissive suffix match that does not enforce a dot-boundary, allowing unrelated domains that merely end with the allowed suffix to pass validation.

For example, with the default ALLOWED_HOSTS of ['*.mongodb.net', ...], a malicious host like evil-mongodb.net incorrectly passes the check because 'evil-mongodb.net'.endsWith('mongodb.net') evaluates to true, even though it is not a subdomain of mongodb.net.

This enables an attacker who can redirect a victim's connection (via DNS poisoning, SRV record manipulation, or config tampering) to bypass the OIDC host restriction and capture authentication tokens.

Applications using OIDC authentication may leak credentials to attacker-controlled servers that bypass the host allowlist via lookalike domains (e.g.,
{code:java}
evil-mongodb.net
{code}
). This can lead to account takeover, unauthorized database access, and potential data breaches. Organizations using MongoDB Atlas with OIDC SSO are particularly at risk.
h2. Details
h4. Scenario: 1
h5. node-mongodb-native-main/src/utils.ts:83-94
{code:java}
**
 * Determines if a connection's address matches a user provided list
 * of domain wildcards.
 */
export function hostMatchesWildcards(host: string, wildcards: string[]): boolean {
  for (const wildcard of wildcards) {
    if (
      host === wildcard ||
      (wildcard.*startsWith('*.')* &amp;&amp; host?.*endsWith*(*wildcard.substring(2, wildcard.length)*)) ||
      (wildcard.*startsWith('*/')* &amp;&amp; host?.*endsWith*(*wildcard.substring(2, wildcard.length)*))
    ) {
      return true;
    }
  }
  return false;
}
{code}
h2. Recommendations

Modify
{code:java}
hostMatchesWildcards()
{code}
to require a dot-boundary before the matched suffix or set explicit, stricter
{code:java}
ALLOWED_HOSTS
{code}
in connection options.

 
----
h3. Risks/Unknowns
 * _What could go wrong while implementing this change? (e.g., performance, inadvertent behavioral changes in adjacent functionality, existing tech debt, etc)_
 * _Is there an opportunity for better cross-driver alignment or testing in this area?_
 * _Is there an opportunity to improve existing documentation on this subject?_

Inadvertently allowing previously-blocked addresses, or blocking or previously-allowed addresses.
Cross-driver testing in this area is necessary, we don't know if only Node is impacted.

h3. Acceptance Criteria
h4. Implementation Requirements
 * Host `evil-mongodb.net` does not match wildcard `*.mongodb.net`

h4. Testing Requirements
 * Tests for host `evil-mongodb.net` and wildcard `*.mongodb.net`
Add more tests to cover other scenarios. Ensure all existing tests are passing without changes.

h4. Documentation Requirements
 * None

h4. Follow Up Requirements
 * -Confirm other drivers don't have a similar issue.-

h3. Description
The type signature of the EJSON.stringify() function allows parameter combinations that don't work as expected. Specifically, when options are passed as the second parameter and space as the third parameter, the space argument is ignored.

h3. Problem
The current type signature of stringify is:
{code:js}
function stringify(
  value: any,
  replacer?: (number | string)[] | ((this: any, key: string, value: any) => any) | EJSONSerializeOptions,
  space?: string | number,
  options?: EJSONSerializeOptions
): string
{code}

This signature allows a call like:
{code:js}
EJSON.stringify(object, { relaxed: false }, 2)
{code}

which is used by this in tests within js-bson test/bench/etc/generate_documents.ts

h3. Current Behavior
With this call, the following happens:

{code:js}{ relaxed: false }{code} is passed as the replacer parameter
{code:js}2{code} is passed as the space parameter
The code detects that replacer is an object (but not an array) and treats it as options
In doing so, space is reset to 0, causing the 2 to be ignored
Relevant code in src/extended_json.ts:484-488:
{code:js}
if (replacer != null && typeof replacer === 'object' && !Array.isArray(replacer)) {
  options = replacer;
  replacer = undefined;
  space = 0;  // <-- space is ignored!
}
{code}

h3. Expected Behavior
The call {code:js}EJSON.stringify(object, { relaxed: false }, 2){code} should either:

Option 1: Throw an error or be rejected by the TypeScript compiler
Option 2: Apply the options correctly AND respect the space value of 2

h3. Reproduction
{code:js}
import { EJSON, Int32 } from 'bson';

const doc = { int32: new Int32(10) };

// This variant works as expected:
console.log(EJSON.stringify(doc, undefined, 2));
// Output: {
//   "int32": 10
// }

// This variant does NOT work as expected:
console.log(EJSON.stringify(doc, { relaxed: false }, 2));
// Expected output: {
//   "int32": {
//     "$numberInt": "10"
//   }
// }
// Actual output: {"int32":{"$numberInt":"10"}}
// (space is ignored)
{code}

Run this and try activating the numeric item as indicated in the comments below and it will fail.

{code}
use MongoDB;

main:
{
    my $mc = MongoDB::MongoClient->new(host => "localhost", port => 27017);
    my $mdb = $mc->get_database("test2");

    my $coll = $mdb->get_collection("foo");

    my $doc = {};

    my $rawval;
    my $newval;

    # Try changing this to 1 to activate it and the insert() will                 
    # fail with a type (ref) unhandled error:                                                                     
    if(0) {
        $rawval = 12.3;
        $newval = $rawval;
        $doc->{"V1"} = $newval;
    }

    $rawval = "I am a string";
    print "grooming [$rawval] to a ref [$newval]!\n";
    $newval = \$rawval;
    $doc->{"K1"} = $newval;

    $coll->insert($doc);
}
{code}

If a file in {{fs.files}} collection doesn't have its counterpart(s) in {{fs.chunks}} (e.g. because of a database corruption), both the {{mongofiles}} utility and GridFS Perl driver return an empty string for the file's contents instead of throwing an error.

For example:

1. Put a test file into a GridFS database:

{code}
$ echo Foo > bar
$ mongofiles -d test put bar
$ rm bar
{code}

2. Remove file data in {{fs.chunks}} collection (imitating a database corruption that we have encountered some time ago):

{code}
$ mongo test

> db.fs.files.findOne({filename: "bar"}, {_id: 1})
{ "_id" : ObjectId("549374544c5187fb37c9c675") }

> db.fs.chunks.remove({files_id: ObjectId("549374544c5187fb37c9c675")})
WriteResult({ "nRemoved" : 1 })
{code}

3. Try fetching a file using Perl GridFS driver:

{code:perl}
#!/usr/bin/env perl

use strict;
use warnings;

use MongoDB;
use MongoDB::GridFS;
use MongoDB::Database;
use MongoDB::OID;

use Data::Dumper;

my $conn = MongoDB::Connection->new;
my $db = $conn->get_database('test');

my $gridfs = $db->get_gridfs;

my $file = $gridfs->find_one({'filename' => 'bar'});
print Dumper($file->slurp());
{code}

*Expected:* {{find_one()}} dies because of an inconsistency between {{fs.files}} and {{fs.chunks}}, similar to how {{mongofiles}} throws an assertion.

*Actual:* {{find_one()}} returns an {{IO::File}} object of a zero-length file.

4. Try fetching a file using {{mongofiles}}:

{code}
$ mongofiles -d test get bar
connected to: 127.0.0.1
assertion: 10014 chunk is empty!
{code}

*Expected:* {{mongofiles}} does not create file {{bar}} in the current path.

*Actual:* {{mongofiles}} creates a zero-length file {{bar}} in the current path.

I should also note that MongoDB 2.2.3 that we have used before did behave in a correct way, but 2.6.6 doesn't anymore.

The implication of this bug is that if {{fs.chunks}} gets corrupt / loses data (which it did in our case), it makes it very hard to spot said data corruption because both MongoDB utilities mentioned just continue to silently return zero-length files as valid data.

